      question: "A kidney transplant patient on tacrolimus develops headache and cannot see. The nurse asks 'how many fingers am I holding up?' and the patient responds correctly. Does this rule out cortical blindness?",
      options: ["Yes — the patient can see", "Not necessarily — cortical blindness can be incomplete or fluctuating; continue monitoring visual function serially, and if the patient later reports vision changes or fails visual testing, PRES with cortical involvement should be suspected", "Only if the patient can read", "The test is not valid"],
      correct: 1,
      rationale: "Cortical blindness in PRES can be partial, fluctuating, or complete. A single normal test does not rule it out. Serial visual assessments are essential. Additionally, some patients with cortical blindness have anosognosia — they are unaware of their visual loss and may confabulate responses. Always correlate with the clinical picture."
